<Text>First time here and it was an event. We will comeback again and again. Delicious and unlike other places in bay area, chef amazing knowledge, care and artistic attention that makes an evening simply amazing. Cheers!!!</Text></record></dataset><record>
<text>Sushi Sho is definitely my favorite sushi experience. It's a slow paced, delicious meal with Aki-San. He's an absolute legend and will tell you about each piece of food you're about to eat, and what to do to have the perfect experience. The cold smoked salmon is a rarity and absolutely amazing. Also, probably the only place to do Anago (marine eel) justice. Everything is delicious. Come in with the mindset to enjoy the experience and savor every bite.

Note: Sushi Sho is by reservation only and, despite the large interior, he only has two seatings per day of 6 people each. This is a personalized dining experience.< /text>< gmapID>
0x8085794b6a1c7e05:0xe1dea5bf8f33d584<//gmapID>

</record></dataset><record>
< Review>
Sushi Sho was always my favorite place for sushi when they were located on upper Solano Avenue. I have not visited their new location, which opened after a long pause in between., as I have moved away from the Bay Area. Aki-san is a master sushi chef,  albeit a bit eccentric, and will not settle for anything less than the best quality and dining experience. As he is the only chef preparing food at the counter (with his wife helping out with other chores), Aki-san would rather turn away customers than have them waiting too long. This is why you may see empty spots and yet be turned away. But believe me, you will not find better, fresher fish more expertly prepared than with Aki-san.  Two dishes that stand out, beside all the others, are the Usuzukuri sashimi and the Chawan mushi, a custard with bits of fish and a ginko nut, and probably the best one I've ever had. Lastly, if you ask nicely, you can probably get tamaki  (hand roll) sushi, even though it isn't on the menu.  Sushi-sho is about enjoying the intimate  experience (and the food, of course). You will not find another place like this anywhere.</Review>

5-stars is unequivocal. Aki San had been making sushi for 4 decades. He takes deep pride in making everything from scratch. His own unagi sauce. Cold smoking his own salmon. Sourcing the finest fish. It is a mom and pop tip quality sushi restaurant. Be forewarned... 2 seatings of 6 at the bar only!</text>

<review>It was a very challenging and fun hike. There is more than enough room for parking, so if you know you're gonna challenge yourself, you can pretty much park next to the entrance of the trail. The hike is ALL uphill and the steep terrain can be very slippery and difficult to navigate. This hike is not easy by any means and nike shoes are definitely not recommended. Once at the top, you have spectacular views of the Burbank, Glendale, and Griffith park areas. This trail even leads up to Mount Thom so if you're feeling extra adventurous, check it out. I definitely recommend.</review><username>Daniel Lamas< /username></record>
</dataset><record>
< text>
The statue of Miss American Green Cross at its trailhead is a beautiful reminder of early American reforestation history. Sculpted by Frederick Willard Potter in 1928 as a symbol of conservation movement in the U. S. and particularly Glendale to save the forests of America.</text>

<userid>116322971398258236871< /userid><username>Millie Chang</username>< date>

<Rate>4<//Rate>< text>
hidden gem of a hike behind the suburbs of glendale! free parking near the library. i saw two trailheads, my friend and i took the "seven trees one." it is quite steep so beware. wear proper shoes, bring sunscreen, and water for sure! the path is dirt/gravel so can be slippery at times. the views of glendale/burbank are pretty neat! unfortunately, it was quite smoggy today. there are many forks in the road, with not too much signage. my friend and i ended up going higher up the mountain and traversed along the verdugo motorway and the brand motorway, until finally making it back to the parking lot (7 miles). more signs/maps would be helpful... we were scared we got lost a few times! there were not too many people on the trail, which was nice. also water fountains/restrooms would be great additions to the trails!<//text>

< username>
Josh Rickards</username>
<text>This restaurant is perfect if you're staying at Mission Bay Resort otherwise I'm not sure it's worth travelling just to visit Covewood for the food with so many great options in San Diego, however to meetup and have a drink, this checks all the right boxes.
Covewood has a very comfortable and stylish vibe. The outdoor seating has firepits and views galore. The entrees are small in portions and if you're really hungry, I'd suggest going elsewhere. The food does have amazing taste, you won't be disappointed in that department. They did have a kids menu so overall Covewood is great. I think the only drawback is the portion sizes, it's really more like a place to have appetizers and drinks with a great vibe and views.

< Review>
This is one of the best storage facilities I've ever used!! Great prices and clean units!!!
Me and family recently relocated from Bakersfield to Shafter and were down sizing. But we didn't want to lose things we cherish doing so (like my grandmas antique china cupboard and paintings she left me) so we began the hunt for a storage facility near our new home. I called around a few places. They were either to far or the person on the phone was just rude. So i decided to stop in a place and hope for the best. Purely Storage on Elm was the first place i actually went into and I was super relieved to find the help i needed. The manager was was knowledgeable and was able to answer all my questions with certainty. She was polite, courteous, and very patient, as i had my 2 boys with me who are very energetic lol. Thank you Theresa Soerjono for making my move easier!!<//Review>

< Text>
I cleaned out my closet and took a basket of 29 items in; all clean, folded, some in dry cleaner bags. All are nice name brands like J Crew, White House/Black Market, BCBG. The woman who took them in, Teresa, told me it would take 45 minutes to do the intake/pricing. I decided to wait in the store. The store was empty, save for one other shopper who didn't buy anything and a lady who brought in a purse which they rejected and she left. Meanwhile, my basket remained untouched while the two staffers chatted with each other and messed around with hangers. I got the distinct impression that neither of them wanted to bother with the pricing, and each was waiting for the other to go do it. After half an hour, Teresa went over to the basket, lifted the top item and looked at the tag, ran her finger down the stack in the basket, lifted one corner, and called me over and told me they wouldn't be taking any of them because they are "out of date."  I guess she is psychic, since she did not bother to remove or unfold a single item to look at it.
I felt this was extremely disrespectful to me as a customer. If it was too much work to take in items on their shift, I wish they had told me when I came in, instead of keeping me waiting and wasting a half hour of my time. I will not be back.</Text>

<userid>115134221127176328845<//userid><username>Ben Vorspan<//username>< date>
1519615809609</date>
<rate>4<//rate>< text>
For kosher pizza, it's pretty good. Compared to non kosher pizza, it's bland and expensive. Other foods are generally pretty good. Large selection of vegetarian foods, including Mexican, Greek salad, stuffed pretzels and desserts. Order at the counter and they'll bring you the food, but that's about all the service you'll get. They won't check on you, and if it's crowded you'll be lucky even to get a cup of water. Id recommend taking your food to go rather than eating there.</text>

< text>
Why does Kosher always equal rip-off? There is no reason that a vegetarian pizza should be over $20 and every other item is at least double what it costs anywhere else. When a menu item says it contains certain ingredients, it should! Our Greek Salad did not have any red onion. And a Greek Salad doesn't have Ranch dressing, folks. We weren't even given a choice of dressing. Why don't you have a real Greek dressing? When you list "chicken" you must say it's tofu. So why do you call it "chicken"?  The pizzas we got were not cooked long enough.

The food is pretty good, that much I'll give Brami's. But the price is outrageous, insulting. For 2 vegetarian pizzas, an eggplant parm, 3 salads, it cost around $90. Come on - get real, Brami's.< /text>

<Name>Mary Peerman</Name><Date>1623017516394</Date>< review>
I usually never leave negative reviews but felt my voice needed to be heard here.  But first the good news... We ate outside and it was lovely, a beautiful place in midtown, most of the servers were nice and did check on us... I say ‚Äúservers‚Äù because you are not assigned one.  Although the food was good ... order the salmon bowl, it was delicious... my enchiladas were just okay... the requirement to order everything through the app was just so impersonal.  They are trying to reach out to the younger crowd, but what about us mid-lifers who actually have the money to spend at these more upscale Mexican restaurants?  I want to order with a server who can take all my special requests without having to navigate my phone app wearing my ‚Äúreaders‚Äù.  This is not just a Covid  thing, we asked one of five servers  who came to check on us.  This is the way it is.  A sign of the future? II sure hope not.</review>

< text>
A great brunch place if you are around the area or it's even better if you live around there because you don't have to look for breakfast. I met up with my friend here to grab some lunch. The hardest part about this place is finding parking, I parked in a paid structure since it was easier. We got seated outside and had to scan a QR code for the menu. I got the French Toast with water because I saw getting a Pepsi was pretty pricy. The French toast was delicious especially since I haven't had it in a while. The chips and salsa was also great. Our server came back frequently to check on us. You put your oder through the website so everything is all done digitally.<//text>

3</rating>
< review>
I hope the owner of this restaurant is paying attention.
You are losing 15% of sales because you're forcing people to order from an app and that's on a regular day you're losing 20 to 25% on a busy day.

I work for a data collector where it shows that people are less willing to buy more food or drinks from an app.

Being served at a restaurant by a waitress is part of the full  restaurant experience  technology will never replace comfort or a waiter. A waiter can just get more food or drinks by just asking him which leads to more food and drink sells.

I will also stop leaving tips for waitresses or Waiters if they don't take my order.

Let your Waiters serve their customers and let customers have a full restaurant experience where they're willing to spend more money if they had a real menu in front of them.< /review>

< review>
Went for a date night on a Thursday and was pretty happy with everything for the most part. Just a couple of disappointing points on the food.. the chips before the meal were cold and didn't taste very fresh. I ordered the mole enchiladas with chicken and cheese and--while the filling was delicious--the mole was overly sweet and was lacking any hint of chili peppers. The cilantro rice was definitely delicious and kind of stole the show on the plate for flavor.

If you're going to have a drink, I would highly recommend the blackberry margaritas, they're tart and delicious! I had mine with the casamigos silver tequila and it was fantastic. Our server was also attentive and kind. Great service overall even though they were very busy!</review>

< Name>
Debbie Albert<//Name>
<Time>1538277639094</Time><rating>5< /rating><text>All i can say is OMG!!!  Got to admit that after my one year stint in Plano, TX, it took about a year before I ever wanted any barbeque or Mexican food.  We have eaten at Tres Hermanos, Chevy's--but hadn't found the favorite Mexican place until by happenstance, we ended up at Zocalo.  Starting with their amazing chips served free with great salsa and bean dip, you can really not go wrong beyond that.  The menu has two traditional soups, 4 ceviche options, tacos, empanadas, burritos, and several special dishes unique to Zocalo.  We tried the shrimp ceviche with Zocalo hot sauce as an appetizer.  A little tip, the hottest ceviche is "Ceviche Verde".  Zocalos hot sauce is not very hot.  The waiting staff was helpful with this choice because my hubby can't take the heat (I will come back for the verde with my son or a friend).

For the main dish, my husband and I shared the enchiladas en mole.  I have had mole dishes in Mexico and in several states in the U.S.  This is by far the best mole ever.  I honestly think I will have dreams about this sauce for days to come.  Sadly, it was so good that I may have difficulty ordering anything else on the menu.  Which is a real shame because that would be way too many options for me to pass up!<//text>< Pictures>

< review>
I love their drinks and ambient, though the food is too americanized for my taste: too much sauces, mayo, etc. on the tacos and too little cilantro, guacamole, pico de gallo, y queso fresco. But the home made tortillas are great! Atmosphere is very pleasant and stylish, and the fancy selection of margaritas is impressive. I have never been unhappy with any of them so far! Highly recommended for a date, dinner with friends or any other occasion to enjoy a good margarita in midtown.</review>

<Text>I have been meaning to try this place for a while. I am not a local, but my past couple of trips here had been pretty short. I did not have the chance to dine in, but trust me when I say I wish I had!! Ordered to go and was ready in 15 minutes. When I got there, the aroma and the stunning decor could only be further impressed by the staff and their warm and friendly demeanor. As I was leaving Los Fabulosos Cadillac began to fill the last of my senses. As we were getting to our hotel, the smell filled the car and literally made my mouth water! We ordered the Tortilla Soup for a rainy day, Enchiladas en Mole and Chile Relleno lunch specials. Let me begin by saying WOW GAME OVER! This is a MUST try when in Sacramento! The taste is not only authentic but left me wanting to dine in and really dive into the full experience. Excellent taste, tender on all bites...wow! I will make some time next time I am in town! The pictures cannot even begin to properly give justice to the taste.<//Text>< gmap_id>

Tremendous Mexican food in an exciting part of Midtown.  I was blown away by the quality of the enchiladas, and I had the opportunity to try three different styles. <review>I have been a Zocalo fanatic for years. I often come here for special occasions with family, bring out of town friends here for a taste of Sacramento, and have enjoyed many wonderful date nights. I requested Z√≥calo delivery for my quarantine birthday and my sweet friend ordered it for me, and the quality was excellent.

The decor of this restaurant is really awe inspiring. They take such care and meaning into their interior design and each restaurant has different gorgeous details to explore. I‚Äôve tried a handful of food and drinks off the menu and have loved everything they make.

The only negative I have to say is that we almost always have terrible service. I‚Äôve had a feeling this is due to profiling, but I hope that‚Äôs not true. We get neglected for too long at the beginning, have too few check backs and don‚Äôt get offered refills, plate clearing, etc. This can be really frustrating but the amazing food and gorgeous atmosphere always bring us back.

We have made a complaint once before and the manager was generous enough to comp our whole bill and give us his business card to let him know when we‚Äôd be coming back so he could arrange great service.

This most recent visit, we (group of 2) called not far in advance and inquired if there was availability, since I know most places are requesting reservations (Mid June 2020). Emoni talked to me on the phone and was very friendly and helpful. She arranged for us to come in 45 mins. Since it was last minute, we sat on their street side patio. Emoni was so sweet and welcoming and led us to our table and made sure it was in the shade. It was a very hot day and it was very frustrating that we sat there for 15 minutes without being greeted. We went back to the host stand to let them know no one had come by. Then a girl who looked like a host came by to take our drink order, and we put in food as well. A few mins later a guy swung by with utensils but still no chips or water (like they normally do) and a full ten mins after we ordered, the food came. I frustratedly let the food runner know we still hadn‚Äôt even received our drinks and he was very apologetic. Our drinks arrived along with our food a minute later, a full 25 mins after sitting at our table. No one ever introduced themselves as our server. At that point we wanted to quickly enjoy our drinks and small bites and get out of there. The fish tacos on the happy hour menu were fantastic, as was the blackberry margarita, although I thought the marga would have been better with a salt rim than sugar.

Thank you Zocalo for providing such exquisite meals on a regular basis for me and my family. I‚Äôm sorry for the novel, but I hope the thorough review is helpful.</review><Rating>3</Rating>< GmapID>

< Review>
We visited for the first time based on a recommendation. We were thoroughly impressed by the service and delicious menu. The decor is beautiful too. For the appetizer we ordered the empanadas. And for dinner we ordered the fish and asada tacos. The meal arrived at the table the same time as the appetizer! Great fast service. Everything was fresh and delicious! I would highly recommend it. As a special treat the manager came by and brought us a free piece of their made from scratch Tres Leches cake with fresh berries on top. This was the perfect way to end a great meal. Thanks Zocalo. We enjoyed our visit. (Almost forgot, they provide chips, salsa and beans- also delicious)</Review>

<text>We are here last night and everything about this place was fantastic. The  margaritas were fresh and top notch. The manager brought over an appetizer sample that was yummy. I had a salad with salmon & my husband had a burrito. Neither one of us was starving; we had a big lunch earlier, but we ate everything because it was so delicious we could not stop. We also had the chocolate cake desert. I love cake and I am a cake snob- it was the BEST cake I ever had. Also, our waiter was outstanding in every way and the hostesses were adorable. The atmosphere is wicked good and it is now our most favorite restaurant here in Sac.</text><Pictures>None</Pictures>< Resp>

< text>
One of my favorite midtown restaurants... I love their cilantro rice... This is always such a great place to come to either with a large group or with just a dinner companion... The service is what always stands out... I like things very plain so I order exactly what I want a la carte and they always smile and are happy to accommodate me which is really quite wonderful especially when you don't or can't eat a lot of things... Also each and every service staff seems to make an effort to make the visit enjoyable... One of management came by to bring us a glass of sangria just for the heck of it... It's the little touches like that that make the difference in a dining experience... The food is wonderful and the presentation is very creative and beautiful as is interior design and ambiance and location :-)<//text>

< Text>
Absolutely outstanding service, absolutely outstanding food..period...Wow!!!!Jose the shift lead was totally on top of everything having to do with our dining expeirence. Give that guy a raise owners!!!! It's our new fav, period end of story!!

Ok back again.
We made reservations for a party of 5, and requested a specific table. We arrived and quickly parked by the valet staff.  We walked inside and were quickly greeted by the hostess.  We were seated at the table we had requested.  Our server came to our table quickly and introduced herself and took our drink orders.

Jose Lastra the shift lead came to our table and asked if everything was going well, then continued on checking on other guests tables.  The timing of our appetizers and our main dishes was flawless. The quality of all the of our food was excellent in the least.  Order anything and everything at will!! Everything we have ever ordered has been consistantly delicious!

Again, Jose Lastra stopped by a couple times during our dinner to check in on us, this guy know how to make guests feel like king's and queens.  His professional touch makes your visit feel like a personal experience.  We travel and eat out in a lot of places, in my opinion this guy exemplifies what it is to take care of customers and keep them coming back.  The treatment we have received at Zocalos is easily the best we have had in NorCal.  If I owned a restaurant I would want this guy working for me.

As a whole I can't say enough about this place. From beginning to end it's  been flawless.<//Text>

<Rating>5<//Rating>< UserId.>
112688313270209604848</UserId.>
< review>
Love my zocalos!
.
Love their cilantro green rice . Literally that's everything. I love how the rice has so much flavor and goes with everything.
.
I love coming here for their chef dinner. The monthly chef dinner is every first Monday of the month. I love how the menu is different each month and surprise menu for each menu.
.
Each chef monthly dinner comes with a welcome on the house appetizers, a appetizer from the set menu, entree, and dessert. Each course comes with cocktail, beer, or wine. And 30 per person.
.
I love how each month have their themes and we as a big group would all dress accordingly and have lots of fun.
.
Parking is easy because there are plenty of street parking, and next block over on 17th street is only 2 dollar parking.
.
Overall if you haven't been to zocalos try their tortilla which is a must because its home made and its sweet. As well their cilantro rice which is green and so yummy.  They serve brunch and happy hour which is great for certain days. Definitely a great place for dinner because of the vibe and great brunch on Sunday because of the lovely patio. Anyways thanks for reading where do you like to brunch at?<//review>

<user>108087643905600994051< /user>< username>
Daniel Rodriguez< /username>
<Date>1408860677139</Date><rate>4<//rate>< review>
The place is nice and upscale, seats in and outside. I'd take a date here (not a first one, though). The food is pretty darn good, tried the fish tacos and carnitas plate. The portions aren't necessarily a lot, but it'll fill you up. Got an appetizer on the house after being seated, which was nice...not sure if they thought I was someone. Meals average to $14-18. The staff seems to be a hit or miss. The first time, I sat outside dressed very casually and we never got refills on dips, one refill with water and checked on once (I'm fine with that). The second time I dressed nice and sat inside, as soon as my water got half way, dip/rice/beans ran out they would ask if I wanted a refill. So unsure if you're appearance or seating influence service, maybe just the waiter< /review>

< Review>
Food is excellent,  presentation is excellent, experienced wait staff and support is excellent.
Parking is atrocious but there is valet service. Neighborhood for the most part is clean and safe (except for the low rent housing across the street that has iron fencing... to keep the natives in)
Avoid parking on that side of the street. Or you might be confronted by one of the residents of the low rent housing since I think they believe they own that side of the street.
Good News Dog Lovers! Outdoor seating and space allows for your best friend to dine with you!
There's a most excellent craft brewery next door that, if your a beer lover, should try!< /Review>

<review>I have visited both the Roseville location and the Zocalo Midtown location,  and initially thought that Zocalo Midtown was the best. After my last visit on October 19, 2018 I am beginning to question that. My family and I drove from Reno to the Zocalo Midtown which is over two hours away only to receive terrible service. I had told my mother who was visiting from Las Vegas how amazing this place was, but after visiting I was embarrassed to have driven all the way out there for nothing. When we were sat we were greeted by a very lovely server who was super pleasant but even her great attitude could not make up for the poor service the host and bartender provided us with. The host walked by our table and asked my mother if she needed water or any additional chips and salsa while we waited for our food, which she said yes to. He never did bring these things to our table though. He walked back and forth near our table about five times but never actually  brought any of the things that he offered. We sat there and waited for things because our server was busy with lots of other tables. We had not made a big deal out of this but then a table with three gentlemen was sat right behind us. The host who appeared to know them ran over to their table and shrieked in excitement to see his friends, gave them all hugs, and took their alcohol order. It wasn't even a minute after they had ordered when he was back with their drinks. Shortly afterwards two more gentlemen joined the party of three and the same thing happened. This time the bartender who appeared to also know them, walked over their drinks immediately and gave them hugs and asked how he could make their visit even better. Meanwhile, my family and I sat there waiting over 5 minutes to get our drinks or to have anyone approach us to see if we needed anything extra. This was an awful experience and it is not okay to provide such blatant and awful service to customers who are not your friends!!!</review>< username>

Essentially to Polo hard tacos complete with refried beans and cilantro green rice. It was a nice lunch under $20 with an iced tea. I highly recommend attending on Cinco de Mayo at least once in your life it's a festive fun event with lots of fun people and thirst quenching libations. <Rating>5<//Rating><Resp>None<//Resp><username>David Kim<//username><Gmap_id>0x809ad0db8e85f9d3:0x93970692f99a73a7</Gmap_id>< text>
3 highlights about this place below.

Came from the East Bay to visit a friend in sac town, and we ate here. Despite my perception of the capital as being an area desolate of good restaurants when compared to SF/Oak, I was pleasantly surprised by this place. I think this is one of the best Mexican(?) restaurants I've been to. Why?

1. Ambiance - elegant but unpretentious. I feel you could come here for a nice dress-up dinner date but also just to grub with the guys. Has an ancient Hanging Gardens of Babylon type of feel - high ceilings, indoor greenery, spacious tables and comfy seats.

2. Food - Was impressed from the get-go - the complimentary tortilla chips and bean/mole dip was so good. We had like 5 refills. The tortillas were something amazing and took all their dishes (including my fish tacos) to the next level.  Not your plain ol' tortilla, but had a good thickness and chew/softness to it. We had the ceviche, guacamole, quesadilla for starters and everything was great. I got the fish tacos and my friends got the skirt steak and featured special plate - the dishes were flavorful but not overdone.

3. Portion per $ - this place ain't cheap and the nice ambiance had me scared this would be one of those fancy places where a $17 taco dish would come with one dinky taco. But I was wrong. 3 hefty tacos plus rice and beans on the side was more than filling and totally worth the price. In fact, our group of 5 hungry dudes had leftovers even though one of us didn't order a main dish (we did have 3 appetizers we shared though).

Legit.<//text>

<UserId.>101603875665750064777<//UserId.>< Text>
One of the best Mexican restaurants in midtown (and Roseville), let alone one of the best restaurants period. Beautiful, light and airy, vibrant and the food is superb. Try the empanadas, and of course the carnitas, but everything here is great. The staff are super friendly and happy hour is especially good value. Kids get ice cream and a churro at the end of the meal.</Text>

< Text>
Just wanted to HIGHLY recommend Zocalos as one of the top kid friendly restaurants to visit in town. I hadn't realized that going with kids in tow was an option given that the location feels elegant, but was AMAZED by how they nailed it on being pro family. This is a great place to teach little ones restaurant manners.  Here is a summary of everything that Zocalos did tonight to make it a great dining experience for the kids:
1) rearranged their seating plan so that we could have a booth,
2) awesome happy hour menu 7 days per week ($5 margaritas y'all and $5 tacos),
3) super kids menu and reasonably priced,
4) brought the kids juice in cool take home cups (no charge for the drinks or cups),
5) brought the kids churros and ice cream (no charge),
6) the waiters went out of their way to be fast and accommodating, and
7) two of the managers were the ones that kept checking on us and bringing the kids juice and churros,
8) fun coloring and crayons.
They really nailed it. I asked if we got some kind of special treatment or if they go out of their way like this for all families. The manager has a 9 month old and was just so totally into kids and welcoming and yes he confirmed that this is how they host families. Also, the other patrons around us were all happy to see the kids at the restaurant too. The noise level is high enough too that it would be hard for anyone to hear if the kids get loud. This restaurant gets a 10+!<//Text>

At Zocalo had an amazing time love the food and the staff they're all amazing!< /text>

< user_name>

<GmapID>0x809ad0db8e85f9d3:0x93970692f99a73a7< /GmapID><pics>None</pics><review>Great atmosphere, quality and delicious Mexican food. The Basa fish; is what dreams are made of<//review>< rate>
5</rate>
</record></dataset><record>
<text>I love good Mexican (or pseudo Mexican) restaurants.  I have two criteria for judging  Mexican restaurants:  (1) Do thay make a respectable margarita, and (2) how is their chili relleno?

Zocalo's margarita is respectable; a sold B+.  The chili relleno...meh.  It was tasty, but nothing like a traditional relleno.  It was fully stuffed with delicious slow-cooked pork, cheese and other goodness.  That part was outstanding.  However, it was coated with what looked and tasted like corn meal mixed with chili powder, and then deep fried.  Not a fan of that approach.  The result was a thin, brittle, and slightly burnt-tasting coating that did not adhere to the chili at all. Think deep-fried enchilada, but with a chile pepper instead of a tortilla.  My grade for the relleno: C-.  The meat inside was dee-lish-us!

The service was good (B+), although I found it funny that the server pointed out a dish that is "unique" to Zocalo: Cochinita Pibil.  NOT unique at all.  I've eaten at two other Mexican restaurants this week, and both had cochinita pibil on the menu. It's a great dish, and I may order it the next time I am there. Based on the tastiness of the filling in the relleno, I would bet a margarita that it is very good.

In sum: I will definitely be going back.  A good margarita is hard to come by, and there is much more to explore on the menu.</text><Rating>3</Rating>< Pictures>
None<//Pictures>
